name: Omí Saidé
meaning: Among practitioners of Cuban Òrìṣà tradition, Omi Saide is said to mean "the crown of water." In actuality, the cuban orisa name Omí Saidé is derived from the Yorùbá name Omísè̩hìndè. It means "water remained after (as replacement)." Omi (water) is a prefix used for a number of names for devotees of Yorùbá river deities such as Yemo̩ja, Erinlè̩, etc. The name can suggest a series of abiku or still births where intervention by one of the water deities prevented further child deaths. It can also mean that after a series of only girls that a boy was born at long last. An alternate version of this name is Omísè̩hìndé, meaning "water has arrived finally." This suggests that after period of barrenness a baby arrived with the help of a water deity one paid devotion to.
extended meaning:
This name is used in the cuban Santería/Lucumí community for initiates of Yemayá (Yemo̩ja in Yorùbá language). Yemayá is a sea goddess among practitioners of cuban orisa tradition, derived from Yemo̩ja that is a prominent river deity among the Yorùbá people.

***
Omí Osaindé is another Cuban rendition which they (cuban practitioners) believe means: “the water that hits the reefs.” This was the Lukumi name of Trinidad Torregrosa, important bata player and constructor of drums. See : http://www.desmemoriados.com/trinidad-torregrosa/
gloss: [{'omi': ' - water, used as a prefix for names of water deities such as Yemo̩ja, Erinlè̩,  etc.'}]

name: Onígà

name: Onígbógi
meaning: The skillful, dexterous, one (in a particular field).
extended meaning:
'My grandmother and uncles generally understand the name to mean "akíkanjú ènìyàn" (i.e. a very brave person). This semantic interpretation might be partly hinged on the fact that my great-great-great (don't know the exact one, really) was a "great" warrior. They also argue that the full stretch of our own name is: Olúgbogí-Àrán ("àrán", being velvet, a kind of highly valued fabric, serves in this context as an extended metaphor for a sophisticated person (whether as a hunter or as a wealthy fellow)). Taken together, these ethnographic sources suggest to me that the name Gbogí may roughly mean "a very brave and/or sophisticated person" or put differently “a person of high status in a town”. Compare Yorùbá “Gboogi” which roughly translates as “important.” ' - Tósìn Gbógi (via email)

This is the maiden name of my grandmother, which in turn was the name of my great-grandfather Onígbógi, which was shortened to Ogbogi. We are from Ìlárá-Mokin in Ondo State. Based on what I've learned, Onigbogi translates to one who is experienced or matured in their respective jobs. Also, láti gbó means to be brave, so it could also translate to someone that is brave in their livelihood. 
- Stephen Ogunbiyi

Thanks for the great work you are doing on all our behalf. Best. Q"

The Otù root signifies the bearer as a member of the Òṣùgbó society in Ogun State (Source: Babalọlá & Àlàbá: 2003), among the Ìjẹ̀bú. It is also used, as in this case, to refer to the head of such a family the same way as Olú or Ọlá or Àyàn is used to signify not just the real intended meaning but also the icon of the family; in this case, the child as a leader of the pack.

According to Babalọlá & Alàbá (2003), this name can also be read to mean "My being an elder or a member of the Òsùgbó society has given me knowledge."

name: Oñí ocán

It is a name typically given to the initiates of Ochún/Oshún (Ò̩s̩un in Yorùbá language) This name is derived from the Yorùbá name "Oyínkán," which is the abbreviation of either "Oyínkánsádé" (honey dripped onto the crown - of our royal lineage) or "Oyínkánsó̩lá" (honey dripped onto wealth/nobility).

name: Ògèdèǹgbé
meaning: The nickname of a famous Ìjẹ̀shà warrior.
extended meaning: Ògèdèngbé was a battle-field panegyric and nickname for Òriṣàríyìbí, the famous warrior and the Ọbanlá of Ìjẹ̀shàland. The nickname, Ògèdèngbé, is said to originate from his unique fighting style which involved lifting enemies up above his head. Due to his short height and therefore low centre of gravity, so he is able to stand firm in battle without falling, as he lifts up his opponents before slamming them hard on the ground. On the battlefront, or after returning from war, his panegyric is rendered as, "Ògèdèngbé Agbógungbọ́rọ̀, ati kan kan lójú ogun", meaning, "Ògèdèngbé who craves war as festivals, walks in majestic strides in the face of war" Ògèdèngbé would go on to conquer territories across modern day Yorùbá land and into the present day Edo and Delta States. He is known to bequeath a number of children from women offered to him as gift, concubines or spoils of war across Àkókó, Èkìtì, Ondó, Edo and Delta areas. Today, several descendants of Òrìṣaríyìbí across these areas use the last name, Ògèdèngbé, Ògèdègbé or Ọbanlá. Among others, Òrìṣàríyìbí was decorated as Ògèdèngbé; Balógun of Iléshà; Sẹ́ríkí Àjànàkú of Ìjẹ̀shàland; Generalissimo/Commander-in-Chief of the Èkìtì Parapọ̀ Army and The Ọbanlá of Ìjẹ̀shàland. Source: www.ogedengbe.com

name: Ògúnlolú

name: Ògúnmẹ̀rù

name: Ògúnwẹ̀hìnwò
meaning: Ogun, the god or iron looked back.
extended meaning: Ògún worshipers give their children this name as they believe that Ògún did not forget them.

name: Ògúnwẹ̀mímọ́
extended meaning: See also: Ifáwẹ̀mímọ́, Adéwẹ̀mímọ́, Oyèwẹ̀mímọ́, Ọláwẹ̀mímọ́.
gloss: [{'ògún': ' - Ògún, the Yorùbá god of iron'}]

name: Ògúnwọlá
meaning: The god Ògún has entered our success.

name: Ògúnyalé
gloss: [{'Ògún': ' - the Yorùbá god of war and iron'}]

name: Ògúnyẹmí
meaning: 1. Ògún befits me. 2. Herbs/medicine benefit me.
extended meaning: For the second meaning, the second syllable in the name is stretched to realise the grammatical tone which is elided in the spelling. Hence Òògun-ún-yẹ-mí.

name: Ògúnyọ̀ládé
meaning: Ogun, the god of iron, rejoices in nobility/the crown.

name: Ògúnṣolú
gloss: [{'ògún': ' - Ògún, the Yorùbá god of iron'}]

name: Ògúnṣuà
meaning: 1. Ògún brought good fortune. 2. Also Ògúnṣúà is the title of the king of Modákẹ́kẹ́ (in Ọ̀sun State, Nigeria).

name: Ògúnṣẹ̀yẹ
gloss: [{'ògún': ' - Ògún, the Yorùbá god of iron'}]

name: Ògúnṣọlá
gloss: [{'ògún': ' - Ògún, the Yorùbá god of iron'}]

name: Ògúnadé
meaning: Another way of writing Adéògún: the crown of Ògún.
gloss: [{'Ògún': ' - The god of iron and technology.'}]

name: Ògúnbánjọ
meaning: Ògún is in agreement with me.

name: Ògúnbánwó
meaning: Ògún looks over him for me.

name: Ògúnbíyí
extended meaning: Better written, phonetically, as Ògúnbíyìí or Ògúnbíìyí.
gloss: [{'ògún': ' - Yorùba god of iron and technology'}]

name: Ògúndé
gloss: [{'ògún': ' - Ògún, the Yorùbá god of iron'}]

name: Ògúndòyìnbó

name: Ògúndẹ̀yìn
gloss: [{'ògún': ' - Ògún, the Yorùbá god of iron'}]

name: Ògúnkọ́ládé
meaning: Ògún gathered wealth to bring here.

name: Ògúnladé
meaning: HOMOGRAPH 1. Ògún is the crown. 2. Ogun is what we have covered our head with. 1. Ògún broke forth to come.
gloss: [{'ògún': ' - Ògún, the Yorùbá god of iron'}]

name: Ògúnlọ́wọ̀
gloss: [{'ògún': ' - Ògún, the Yorùbá god of iron'}]

name: Ògúnmókùn
meaning: Ògún has picked up a royal bead. [The full name is "Ògúnmókùnadéró"]
extended meaning: It is the name of a royal family in Ìjẹ̀shà land. Though the family has roots over the whole Yorùbáland, the name is uniquely born only by members of this family who can link their ancestry to the same source!
gloss: [{'Ògún': ' - the god of Iron and technology'}]

name: Ògúnmẹ́kàn
meaning: The god of iron has (picked) an offshoot/offspring.
gloss: [{'ògún': ' - Ògún, the Yorùbá god of iron'}]

name: Ògúnnọ́wọ̀
gloss: [{'ògún': ' - Ògún, the Yorùbá god of iron'}]

name: Ògúnsànyà
extended meaning:
"There are two separate families with the surname as far as I'm aware . One set hail from Ogun state and my family from Ikorodu."

"I'm also an Ògúnsànyà. We hail from Tedé in Ọ̀yọ́ State. Tedé is somewhere near Ṣakí and Àgọ́-Àrẹ.
gloss: [{'ògún': ' - Ògún, the Yorùbá god of iron'}]

name: Ògúntóyè
meaning: Ògún is big enough for honour/chieftaincy.

name: Ògúnwoolu
gloss: [{'ògún': ' - Ògún, the Yorùbá god of iron'}]

name: Ògúnwùsì
gloss: [{'ògún': ' - Ògún, the Yorùbá god of irorn'}]

name: Ògìdán
extended meaning: This is a name given to leopard hunters or their family. The meaning of the name is not easily deduced from the sounds. The praise name of the leopard is "Ògìdán olólà ijù: Lion the chief tribal marker of the jungle." This, perhaps as a result of the sharpness of its claws and teeth, capable of "marking" just any prey.

name: Ògúnníyì
gloss: [{'ògún': ' - Ògún, the Yorùbá god of iron'}]

name: Ògúnnúpẹ̀bí
extended meaning: "The Ìpẹ̀bí is a shrine were prospective kings are required to spend 7 days of isolated traditional prayer activities before their coronation. The deity in the shrine is Ògun hence the name." User feedback
gloss: [{'ògún': ' - Ògún, the Yorùbá god of iron'}]

name: Ògúnǹdójútìmí
meaning: Ògún, my deity protector has never let me down

name: Ògúnríìíkẹ́
meaning: Ògún has found this (one) to cherish/pamper.

name: Ògúntúndé
gloss: [{'ògún': ' - Ògún, the god of iron and technology'}]

name: Ògúnwálé
meaning: The god of war has come home.
gloss: [{'ògún': ' - Ògún, the Yorùbá god of iron/war'}]

name: Òjòlayọ̀
extended meaning: The full saying is "Òjò l'ayọ̀ ìgbín": the rain is the pleasure/happiness of the snail.

name: Òjòpagogo
meaning: The rain is incapable of drowning the voice of the gong.

name: Òjó
meaning: A male child who was born with his umbilical cord tied around his neck.
extended meaning: This is an àmútọ̀runwá (brought from heaven), a name already pre-determined due to the unique nature of their birth.

name: Òkè
extended meaning: Ò̀kè could mean a mountain, hill...usually to describe an elevation. Its been used to describe the name of places characterized by hills and mountain. Òkè-Olúmọ, Òkè-Ìtòkú and Òkè-Láǹtóró in Abẹ́òkuta. Also, it's come to play the role of prefixes to the names of many praying grounds.

name: Òkèdìji
meaning: The mountains have become a shade.

name: Òkètáòlegùn
meaning: A mountain/hill so high that we can't climb it.

name: Òkètókun
meaning: The mountain is as big/prominent/notable as the ocean.

name: Òkètóògùn
meaning: The hill suffices for medicine. [verification needed]

name: Òkètọ̀nàdé
meaning: The hill came back through a path.

name: Òkédáìró
meaning: The deity of the hill spared this one.

name: Òkégbénlé
meaning: The god of the hill has lifted me up.

name: Òkétáyọ̀
meaning: The deity of the hill is enough for joy/happiness.

name: Òkétúmbí
meaning: The hills gave me a rebirth.

name: Òkéyọdé
meaning: The hills have arrived. The child of hills has arrived.

name: Òkéṣeéyìn
meaning: Òkè Ìbàdàn Hill is worthy of worshiping/praising/eulogizing.

name: Òkìkíọlákàn
meaning: The fame of our nobility/success is widespread.

name: Òkunladé
meaning: Crowns are as vast as the sea.

name: Òkúdalàyè
meaning: The dead has become the living.

name: Òkúnmúyìdé
meaning: 1. The ocean brought this (one) 2. The ocean brought value

name: Òkúnrìnbóyè
meaning: The ocean walked in to meet chieftaincy.

name: Òkúrọ̀mádé
meaning: The dead hold on to royalty.

name: Òkúṣàga
meaning: 1. The ancestors made a chair (to camp with me). The ancestors are with me. 2. The Okù deith is with me. [verification needed]

name: Òkújá
extended meaning: Name given to àbíkú children in Benin Republic

name: Ònítirí
meaning: 1. As today is. 2. How is today?
extended meaning: Bí òní ti rí, ọla kò rí bẹ́ẹ̀.

name: Òpómúléró
meaning: Pillar. The one who holds/keeps the family together.

name: Òrìshàgúnà
extended meaning: See also: Ṣàgúnà, Shàgúnà, Òrìṣàgúnà, Òrìṣàgúnnà.

name: Òrìṣàgúnà
meaning: The Òrìsà makes the path straight.
extended meaning: The "òrìṣà" root of this name marks the bearer as coming from the family of òrìṣà worshippers (although many modern bearers do not necessarily continue the practise). The name affirms òrìṣà as the spiritual guide of the child.

name: Òrógbangba
meaning: One who stands firm (like a rod).

name: Òtúnígà
meaning: The (child of the) Otù (the Òṣùgbó secret society) has a royal courtyard. This Otù child is royalty.

name: Òṣémàwé
meaning: The official title of an Ondo king.

name: Oṣàránmayé
meaning: God sent me to the world.

name: Oṣàtógbè
meaning: The deity is worthy of being supported.

name: Oṣóbẹ̀rù
meaning: The Oṣó is worth being feared.
gloss: [{'oṣọ́': ' - sorcerer, Oṣó divinity of fertility and farming, òriṣa oko'}]

name: Oṣódàpọ̀
meaning: The union of a family of the fertility god.

name: Oṣódèyí
meaning: 1. Sorcery held this one down, kept him/her alive. 2. The sorcerer became this.
extended meaning: Meaning #1 could apply to àbíkú children.
gloss: [{'oṣó': ' - sorcery, sorcerer, the fertility god (òrìṣà oko)'}]

name: Oṣófọlábọ̀
meaning: the Oṣó came back with wealth.
gloss: [{'oṣó': ' - sorcerer, Oṣó divinity of fertility and farming, òriṣa oko'}]

name: Oṣónáíyà
gloss: [{'oṣó': ' - sorcerer, Oṣó divinity of fertility and farming, òriṣa oko'}]

name: Oṣóyínká
meaning: 1. I'm surrounded by sorcerers. 2. I'm surrounded by the god of the harvest (Òrìṣà oko)
extended meaning: Another more complex root of the word Oṣó comes from the god/òrìṣà of farming, Òrìṣàokó & agriculture. So, the original name of Oṣóyínká would be Òrìṣàokóyínká. It then was shortened to Oṣóókóyínká, and then to Oṣóyínká. This is the same for all names of Oṣó or Ṣó, however, many of those names may either originate for the òrìṣà or sorcerers in general so the only way to distinguish a name's meaning is knowing the unqique history of every family with the name.

name: Oṣóyẹ̀lú
extended meaning: The name originated from the deity of farming called Oṣọ́. It was believed that the presence of the deity bring prosperity to the life of the occupant of the settlement. Hence, the coinage Osoyelu: every settlement deserves Oṣó.

name: Oṣóṣínà
gloss: [{'oṣó': ' - sorcerer, Oṣó divinity of fertility and farming, òriṣa oko'}]

name: Oṣóyẹmí
meaning: 1. The sorcerer is worthy of me. 2. Òrìshàokó suits me.
extended meaning: Oṣó represents sorcerer but is also a nickname for the god of farming, Òrìṣàokó  (Okó),who was also a sorcerer.
gloss: [{'Oṣó': ' - the sorcerer, the god of farming'}]

name: Oṣùọlálé
meaning: The season of glory has arrived.

name: Oṣésùntọlá
extended meaning: Ṣàngó's oṣé which he uses to channel his thunder & lightning powers.

name: Oṣésúnmọ́lá
meaning: Ṣàngó's wand draws close to this child of wealth.
extended meaning: Ṣàngó uses his wand (oṣé) to channel his lightning & thunder powers.

name: Pamílẹ́rínayọ̀
meaning: Cause me to laugh for joy.
extended meaning: The actual pronunciation of the name is uses an extra ẹ that is omitted in text, i.e. as Pamílẹ́ẹ̀rínayọ̀

name: Pamílẹ́rìn
meaning: Make me laugh. Gladden my heart.

name: Pàímọ́
extended meaning: The name is a prayer to the gods to keep this chid safe from dying. It's a name given to suspected àbíkú children.

name: Péjú
meaning: Be completely around. A short form of a longer name.
extended meaning: Short form of Adépéjú, Olúpéjú, Ọlápéjú, etc

name: Pípéniṣẹ́olúwa
meaning: The work of God is complete.

name: Pẹ̀rọ̀sáyémi
meaning: Invoke ease and calmness into my life.

name: Pọ̀jù
extended meaning: This is a short form of names like Adépọ̀jù, Olápọ̀jù, etc.

name: Pọ̀róyè
meaning: (The child that comes from) a honourable lineage.

name: Pọ́nmilé
extended meaning: This is a common short form of Olúpọ́nmilé or Adépọ́nmilé, etc

name: Rìnmáyọ̀
extended meaning: Most likely a shorter form of "Adérìnmáyọ̀" (the crown walks with joy) or "Olúrìnmáyọ̀" (the lord walks with joy) or "Akínrìnmáyọ̀" (the valiant walks with joy), etc.

name: Rìnsáyọ̀
extended meaning: Most likely a shortened form of "Akínrìnsáyọ" (Valor walks into joy) or "Adérìnsáyọ" (The crown walks into joy) or "Olúrìnsáyọ̀" (The lord walks into joy), etc

name: Ríyìkẹ́
meaning: We've found this one to cherish.

name: Rónkẹ́
extended meaning: This is a short form of Adérónkẹ́, Olúrónkẹ́, Oyèrónkẹ́, etc

name: Rósanwó
meaning: Wait enough to be able to pay.

name: Rótifá
extended meaning: A full form of the name can be "Dúrótifá"

name: Rótìmí
extended meaning: This is the common written form of the name Ọlárótìmí or Olúrótìmí. As Dúrótìmí, it could be read as an àbíkú name.

name: Rúnṣèwé
extended meaning: This is an àbíkú name given to Ìjẹ̀bú children in a positive prayer for their survival.

name: Rẹ̀mí
meaning: 1. Console me. 2. Common short form of a longer name: Rẹ̀mílẹ́kún, Adérẹ̀mí, etc

name: Rẹ̀mílẹkún
extended meaning:
This is a name given typically to a child whose arrival consoled the parents - most times the first child born after a long time of waiting.

See also: Olúrẹ̀mílẹ́kún

name: Rọ́lákẹ́
meaning: I found a treasure to pamper/care for/shield.

name: Rọ́pò
extended meaning:
This is a short form of many names like Adérọpò, Olúrọpò, Firọpò, etc.
This is an abikù name, given to children born after deaths of previous children.

name: Sabẹ́rẹ́dowó
extended meaning: It's a name given to children from the family of tailors.

name: Sanwóolú
meaning: Pay the debt of the family head.
extended meaning: The name can imply many things, chief of which is that the child is expected to triumph enough to take the family back into a lost glory.

name: Sàlàkọ́
extended meaning: Names with "àlà" are usually from devotees of Ọbàtálá, the deity of creation, creativity, and artistry, of whom the plain white cloth is a generally accepted icon. But according to Babalọlá & Àlàbá (2003), this name, Sàlàkọ́, is one given to a child "born with his umbilical cord thrown over a shoulder and brought down along his waist line."

name: Sànyàolú
meaning: Pays back the debt of the lord.

name: Sàràkí
extended meaning: This name comes from Hausa, likely from Basarake (of kingship or aristocrats) or Sarakai (kings, plural of sarki ). More research needed.

name: Sefúnmi
extended meaning: This is most likely a short form of Olúwasefúnmi: the lord did for me.

name: Semílóore
meaning: Be kind to me. Make me a gift.

name: Sèyífúnmi
extended meaning: Most likely a shorter form of "Olúwasèyífúnmi": The lord did this for me.

name: Shàngóbíyì
extended meaning: This is another way of writing Ṣàngóbíyìí
gloss: [{'ṣangó': ' - Ṣangó, the Yorùbá god of thunder'}]

name: Shákúnlé
meaning: Short form of Òrìṣàkúnlé: The Òrìṣà fills the house.

name: Shábà
meaning: User meaning: "The child next to the throne". [verification needed]

name: Shíjúadé
meaning: 1. Open the eyes of royalty. 2. Opens the eyes to see royalty.

name: Shílẹ̀kùnọlà
extended meaning: Usually a shorter form of Olúwaṣílẹ̀kùnọlà

name: Shíttù
meaning: From the Arabic name 'Shiith', the first prophet after Adam. Means "appointed".

name: Shóbíyè
meaning: The sorcerer gave live birth (to this).
gloss: [{'oṣó': ' - sorcerer, Oṣó divinity of fertility and farming, òriṣa oko'}]

name: Shóbẹ̀rù
meaning: The Oṣó is worth being feared.
gloss: [{'oṣó': ' - sorcerer, Oṣó divinity of fertility and farming, òriṣa oko'}]

name: Shóbọ́lá
extended meaning: The meaning makes the name sound like that given to a child born after the death of a prominent member of the family, like a family patriarch.

name: Shófowórà
meaning: What the sorcerer bought with money.

name: Shógbàmímú
gloss: [{'oṣó': ' - sorcerer, the god of fertility, the elders'}]

name: Shógbóyèga
extended meaning:
Jacob Shógbóyèga Odùlátẹ was born in 1884 to the polygamous family of Pa Odulate in Ikorodu, Lagos. Jacob Odulate stopped schooling at the young age of 12 and moved to Abeokuta, Ogun state, at the age of 14 in search of greener pastures... 
Source:  https://oldnaija.com/2018/05/04/the-story-of-jacob-odulate-and-how-he-invented-the-famous-alabukun-powder-in-1918/

name: Shókálù
meaning: The sorcerer is famous around town.

name: Shólàńkẹ́
meaning: Another way of writing Sólàńkẹ́: The sorcerer is who we're taking care of.

name: Shónáìkè
extended meaning: The root oṣó has been interpreted most commonly in two ways: as sorcerer or wizard, but also as Òrìṣà Oko, the fertility god. Context is necessary to decide which one applies in individual cases.

name: Shónẹ́kàn
meaning: The sorcerer has got an offshoot.

name: Shónẹ́yìn
meaning: One with strong ones (or sorcerers) in their bloodline.
extended meaning: "It's Oshó-oun-ní-ẹ̀yin. But it's pronounced in the Rẹ́mọ dialect which means 'I have 'sorcerers' in my bloodline. The word 'sorcerer', I quarrel with because of its negative connotation. We tend to use wizard but that suffer the same fate. I have always just said 'the strong ones', which is a catch-all for brute or spiritual strength. It wouldn't work for this purpose but surely there's a better word." Lọlá Shónẹ́yìn

name: Shórúngbé
meaning: The sorcerer finds someone to carry.
gloss: [{'oṣó': ' - sorcerer, Oṣó divinity of fertility and farming, òriṣa oko'}]

name: Shótáyọ̀
meaning: The fertility god is worth joy.

name: Shódùnkẹ́
meaning: The sorcerer is good to care for, cherish.

name: Shọlá
extended meaning: This is a common shortened form of names like Olúṣọlá, Adéṣọlá, etc.

name: Shọlápé
extended meaning: This is a shorter form of Olúwaṣọlámipé.  Meaning "the Lord has completed my wealth"

name: Shọpẹ́
extended meaning: This is a common short form of Adéṣọpẹ́, Olúṣọpẹ́, etc

name: Shọ́lédolú
meaning: (One who) watch the house until the leader returns.
extended meaning: The name is likely given to a son born in the absence of his father.

name: Similéolúwa
meaning: Rest on the lord. Rely on the lord. Lean on the lord.

name: Simisọ́láolúwa
meaning: Rest in the wealth/benefit of God.

name: Sinmilólú
meaning: Rest or rely on the lord.

name: Sinmilólúwa
meaning: Rest or rely on the lord.

name: Sìndélé
extended meaning: This is a name given to a child born whilst parents are abroad. Short for Sìndéléolúwa.

name: Síjúwadé
extended meaning: The name is also sometimes written as "Síjúadé"

name: Síkírátù
meaning: Memory, recollection, remembrance, thoughts of the past.
extended meaning: Arabic origin. It is the female name version of Zikruhllah. Same meaning

name: Síjúadé
meaning: Opens his eyes to see the crown.

name: Sódẹkẹ́
meaning: The sorcerer has become a rafter (holding up the house).
extended meaning: Another way to read this would be "The sorcerer/fertility god has become our protector." The ẹ̀kẹ́ is a rafter used to support the roof of the house.

name: Sófowóra
meaning: What the sorcerer bought with money.

name: Sógbẹ̀hìndé
meaning: The sorcerer came back in the end.

name: Sólàjà
meaning: The sorcerers have settled the fight.

name: Sóshínà
gloss: [{'oṣó': ' - sorcerer, Oṣó divinity of fertility and farming, òriṣa oko'}]

name: Sótáyọ̀
meaning: The sorcerer is enough for joy.

name: Sóbándé
meaning: The deity of fertility came with me.

name: Sónáriwo
meaning: The devotee of Òrìṣà Oko has joyful noise in their home.
extended meaning:
This name is typically given to celebrate the presence of plenty children (who make joyful noises) around the house where the child was born.
_____

Names beginning with "Ṣó" or "Oṣó" are said to be evolved forms of "Òrìṣà Oko" which is a deity of fertility and harvest, which is usually the family deity of families where these names are given. But in recent times, there have also been regular interpretation of the name as having "Oṣó" mean "sorcerer". Both interpretations are fine, depending on what each bearer and their family prefer.

name: Sóyọyè
meaning: The sorcerer has emerged into a position of honour.
gloss: [{'oṣó': ' - sorcerer, Oṣó divinity of fertility and farming, òriṣa oko'}]

name: Sùlíyá
extended meaning: This name is adapted from an Arabic name. [verification needed]

name: Sùnḿbọ̀
extended meaning: This is a short form of a longer name like Adésùnḿbọ̀, Oyèsúnḿbọ̀, Ọlásùnḿbọ̀...

name: Sùnmọ́nù
meaning: The Yorùbá version of the Arabic name "Usman".

name: Súnkànmí
meaning: Come near me. [A short form of Ọlásúnkànmí]

name: Súàrá
meaning: This name is of Arabic origin "Shu'arah" (Transliterated), meaning "Poet".
extended meaning: This name is also found popular in Indonesia - meaning "sound".

name: Sàrùmí
extended meaning:
A warrior's title in Yorùbáland. 
Sàrùmí dì kaka dì kúkú, kaka lójú ogun - Oríkì

name: Sẹńjọbí
extended meaning:
Ùsẹn is the family totem in honour of an Ijẹ̀bú-Igbó heir apparent, who was sacrificed to avert conquest of the town by enemies.

Source: Odùbáyọ̀ Odùṣínà.

name: Sẹríkí
meaning: Lieutenant. (Probably derived from "Sarkin", the Hausa word for king.)

name: Sẹ̀giladé
meaning: 1. The crown is ornaments of crown. 2. We have crowned ourselves with sẹ̀gi ornaments.

name: Sọlédayọ̀
meaning: To turn the home into joy.

name: Tadénikáwò
meaning: We should be respectful of the influence of the crown (on this child).

name: Tajélawí
meaning: Let talk about business or trade.

name: Talaníbíòsholúwa
meaning: Who do we have if not God?

name: Tanímọ̀wò
meaning: who is able to take care of him/her?

name: Tanítólúwa
meaning: Who is as mighty as God?

name: Tańtọ́lọ́un
meaning: Who is as big and prominent as God?

name: Taraolúwa
meaning: From the body of the Lord. A variation of Tiaraoluwa

name: Tàlàbí
extended meaning: This is a name given to a child born with the umbilical cord thrown over a shoulder and then wound around the waist, resembling a white banner.

name: Tádé
extended meaning: This is a short form of Akíntádé, Olútádé, Oyètádé, etc.
gloss: [{'tó': ' - suffice for, match, as big as'}]

name: Táíyé
extended meaning: It is a name given to the first of twins.

name: Táíwò
meaning: Taste the world. Have a taste of life.
extended meaning: It's a name given to the first of twins, as the first to taste life.

name: Táyé
extended meaning: This is a name given to the first of a set of twins. See: Táíwọ̀.

name: Tèmi
extended meaning:
A shortened form of:
Tèmítọ́pẹ́
Tèmítáyọ̀
Tèmílọlá
Tèmílolúwa
Tèmídayọ̀
Tèmíladé

name: Tèmikóredé
meaning: My are blessings to bring. With my arrival/birth come blessings .

name: Tèmiladé
meaning: Tthe crown is mine. Royalty is mine.

name: Tèmilolú
meaning: 1. Prominence/Leadership is mine. 2. God is mine.

name: Tèmitutù
meaning: Mine are gifts of calm. With my arrival/ birth comes calm(ness).

name: Tèmídáre
meaning: Mine has turned to victory; Mine has become justified.

name: Tèmíjuọpẹ́lọ
meaning: My own is worth giving thanks for and more.

name: Tèmítólúwasìn
meaning: Because of my birth, God is worthy to be praised.

name: Tèmítọ́pẹ́olúwa
meaning: I deserve to continue to give thanks to God.

name: Tèmíyémi
meaning: I am confident with my own decisions.

name: Tèmídayọ̀
meaning: My story has become one of joy. This thing of mine has now been made something to be joyful about.

name: Tiaraolúwa
meaning: From the body of the lord.

name: Tiaraọlá
meaning: An integral part of wealth, honour or value.

name: Tifáṣẹ
meaning: That of Ifá has come true.

name: Tijésù
extended meaning: This is a modern Christian name.

name: Tiléwá
meaning: One that comes from the house.

name: Tinúoṣó
meaning: From the inside of the sorcerer.

name: Titolújù
meaning: God's will is the most prominent/important.

name: Tit́íladé
extended meaning: The "adé" (crown) component of the name shows it as a name given to a royal child.

name: Tiwaladéolúwa
meaning: Ours is the crown of the lord.

name: Tiwalolú
meaning: Prominence is ours. God is ours.

name: Tiwaloreọ̀fẹ́olúwa
meaning: The grace of God is ours.

name: Tiwanioreọ̀fẹ́olúwa
meaning: The grace of God is ours.

name: Tiwatádé
meaning: Ours is worth being crowned for.

name: Tiwátáyọ̀
meaning: Ours is worth being joyful for.

name: Tiwátọ́pẹ́
meaning: We have reason(s) to be thankful.

name: Tìmílẹ́hìn
extended meaning: Typically prefaced with Olú, Adé or Oyè

name: Tìmílẹyìn
extended meaning: Typically prefaced with Olú, Adé or Oyè.

name: Títí
meaning: Forever. Shortened form: Títílọpẹ́ Títílayọ̀ Títílolúwa Títílọlá

name: Títíladùnayọ̀
meaning: Forever is the sweetness of joy.

name: Títílayọ̀miníwájúolúwa
meaning: With God, I can always count on joy. Joy is established for me with God.

name: Títílọpẹ́olúwa
meaning: My gratefulness to God is forever.

name: Tolú
extended meaning: A common short form of Tolúlọpẹ́.

name: Tolújù
meaning: What God wants is most prominent.

name: Tolútọ́pẹ́
meaning: That which is the Lord's is worthy of celebration or thanksgiving.

name: Tòkunbọ̀
extended meaning: This is a common Yorùbá name given to children born abroad and then brought home.

name: Tòwúrọ̀
extended meaning: Could be given to a first child or one conceived in your youth. Also used for a child born after a difficult time.

name: Tóbilọ́ba
extended meaning: This is the shortened form of Olúwatóbilọ́ba.

name: Tófọpẹ́fún
meaning: Worthy to give thanks unto. Worthy to be appreciated.

name: Tókì
extended meaning: This is a common short form of Olútókì or Adétókì.

name: Tókẹ́
meaning: Worth pampering. Shortened form of: Olúwatóké Ọmótóké Ọlátóké Adétóké Oyètóké

name: Tómiláwo
meaning: Sufficient for me as a fraternity.

name: Tómisìn
extended meaning: Short for Olú(wa)tómisìn. Also sometimes written as Tómiísìn.

name: Tóní
meaning: Worth having. Shortened form of: Èyítóní Ọmótóní Ọlátóní Adétóní Ìfétóní

name: Tórera
meaning: Sufficient for delighting oneself. Enough to show off, to be proud of. A child to be pampered... 'Omótómirera' means '[this] child is enough for me to show off (or be proud of)'.
extended meaning: Short form of Adétórera, Omitorera, Ọmọ́tómirera etc.

name: Tótónitolúwa
meaning: God is worthy to be praised.

name: Tówùmí
meaning: That which is attractive to me.

name: Tówùnmí
meaning: That which is attractive to me. That which I want. That which I love.
extended meaning: A longer form of the name is "Olúwaṣeuntówùnmífúnmi: "god has done what I want."

name: Tóyìn
extended meaning: A common short form of "Olúwatóyìn": God/ the almighty is worthy of praise.

name: Tóyìnbó
meaning: Worthy of being praised (until one's lips peel).
extended meaning: This is a shortened form of Adétóyìnbó or Ọlátóyìnbó.

name: Tóyọ̀sí
extended meaning: The full version is usually Olátóyọ̀sí or Adétóyọ̀sí, etc.

name: Tómi
extended meaning: This is a common short form of Ọláolúwatómi.

name: Tómiísìn
extended meaning: Short for Olú(wa)tómisìn. Also commonly written as Tómisìn.

name: Tómílọ́lá
meaning: This (child) is enough for me as success/notability.

name: Tósìn
extended meaning: This is a common short form of the name "Olúwatósìn".

name: Túndé
extended meaning:
This is a common short form.
The full names are Babátúndé (Father returns again) and Yétúnde (Mother returns again).

name: Túnmiṣe
meaning: Renew me. Repair me. Regenerate me.

name: Tútùọlá
meaning: The gentleness of nobility, wealth, success.

name: Túbọ̀sún
extended meaning: This is the short written form of Ọlátúbọ̀sún: Wealth continues to expand.

name: Táyò
extended meaning: This is a commom short version of a long name Ọmọ́táyọ̀, Adétáyọ, Oyètáyọ̀, etc

name: Tìrẹniolúwa
extended meaning: This is a modern Christian name ascribing the arrival of the child to God.

name: Tíèmininimí
meaning: I am the child of/owned by "I am that I am or I am".
extended meaning: 'I am that I am' is one of the names of God, according to the bible. This is a modern Christian name.

name: Tódìmú
extended meaning: It is a short form of "Olúwatódìmú" which translates literally as "The Lord is enough to hold on to".

name: Tẹjúmáiyé
meaning: Fix your gaze on life/living. One with sights set on living.

name: Tẹjúmádé
meaning: Keep a watchful eye on the crown. Stare at royalty (as inspiration or guiding light).

name: Tẹninlánimí
meaning: I belong to the great one.

name: Tẹ̀hìngbọlá
meaning: One who wins their nobility/success in the end.

name: Tẹ̀là
extended meaning: "According to Johnson (p. 83) the name Tẹ̀là was given only to male children belonging to the royal lineages of Ọ̀yọ́."

name: Tẹ̀llà
extended meaning: This is an archaic spelling of "Tẹ̀là"

name: Tẹ̀lúwò
meaning: One who founded a town as trial (exercise).

name: Tẹ̀yìngbọlá
meaning: One who receives nobility in the end.

name: Tẹ́níadé
meaning: Lay the mat of a crown or lay a royal mat.

name: Tẹ́nígbọlá
meaning: Spread the mat to receive nobility/wealth.

name: Tẹ́nígbọrẹ
meaning: One welcomed with glee and enthusiasm.

name: Tẹ́níolú
meaning: 1. Spread a carpet for prominence. 2. Spread a carpet (to welcome) God.

name: Tẹ́níọlá
meaning: Roll out the mat of wealth.

name: Tọlániáwò
meaning: Nobility is what we should pay attention to.

name: Tọmídé
meaning: Came to me. A short from of Akíntọ̀mídé, Oyètọ̀mídé, etc.

name: Tọmọlójù
meaning: Having a child is the greatest concern. The child's well-being is the most important consideration

name: Tọwọ́bọlá
meaning: Puts hands into wealth. Participate in opulence.

name: Tọ̀bùndé
meaning: One recently returned from the market.

name: Tọ̀míwá
extended meaning: Short for Ọlátọ̀míwá, Irétọ̀míwá, Oyètọ̀míwá, Adétọ̀míwá

name: Tọ́lá
meaning: 1. Prominent for success. 2. A short form of longer names like Ọmọ́tọ́lá, Oyètọ́lá, Tọ́lání, etc.

name: Tọ́láṣe
meaning: Improve on success. Make nobility better.

name: Tọ́pẹ́
extended meaning:
Shortened form of:
Tèmítọ́pẹ́
Tiwátọ́pẹ́
Babátọ́pẹ́
Olúwátọ́pẹ́

name: Tọ́ṣọ̀
meaning: A contraction of the name "Ọmọtọ́ṣọ̀", which means the child is worth ornaments.
extended meaning: Probably better spelt as Tóṣọ̀ọ́ for a better pronunciation.

name: Tọ́mọrí
meaning: Full name: Motọ́mọrí: I'm seeing this child again.

name: Ugbódín
meaning: The bush/forest has grown so close together, we can't get in (to bury a dead child).

name: Wáléadé
meaning: Come to the home of royalty.

name: Wáléọlá
meaning: Enter into the house of wealth.

name: Wámidé
meaning: ...Sought me here. [This is a short form of a longer name like Iréwámidé, Ayọ̀wámidé, Ọláwámidé, etc]

name: Wálé
extended meaning: This is a common short form of Ọláwálé, Adéwálé, Ọmọ́wálé, etc

name: Wíndàpọ̀
gloss: [{'iwin': ' - a forest fairy in Yorùbá mythology believed to live in teh ground'}]

name: Wúràọlá
meaning: The glistening part of wealth/nobility. Inestimable jewel.

name: Yanjú
extended meaning: This is a common short form of Adéyanjú or Olúyanjú, etc.

name: Yeyérínsá
extended meaning:
A name given to the child born before/after the immediate departure of a family matriarch. 

See: Babárínsá

name: Yèyéẹwà
meaning: The queen of beauty. Beautiful mother.

name: Yékú
extended meaning:
It is most likely a name given to a child believed to have followed a long line of àbikú children who die as soon as they're born.

'Yeku is an imperative to "stop dying." It is probably a wrong spelling my ancestors settled for but it is different from "Ọ̀yẹ̀kú" (of the Ifa, for example). It is NOT a short form.' - James Yékú

name: Yétádé
meaning: A mother is worth a crown.

name: Yémiítàn
extended meaning: Reflecting the Yorùbá belief that the baby is àbíkú, born to die, this name is an appeal to the child to stop deceiving the parents and actually stay alive.

name: Yésúfù
extended meaning: This form is a Yorubanised form of the Semitic name of the son of Jacob.

name: Yétúndé
extended meaning: The name Yétúnde is often given to female babies that are born around the time of the passing of their mother or grandmother. Their birth symbolizes a "reincarnation" of the deceased woman, hence the meaning: Mother has returned.

name: Yímiká
extended meaning: This is a different way of writing "Yínká".

name: Yínúsà
extended meaning: Based on the Muslim name Yunus (Jonas)

name: Yéwándé
meaning: Mother sought me out to this place.
extended meaning: "Yéwándé is a name given to baby girls born after the loss of a mother or grandmother, usually of one of the parents to the child. I am named Yéwándé. I was born three months premature after my mom lost her mom suddenly. They believe I was in a rush to come to comfort my mom. My mother asked me at the hospital why I came so soon, she asked me "are you my mom?" And I smiled." - User feedback

name: Yẹmí
extended meaning: This is a common short form of Adéyẹmí, Olúyẹmí, Ọláyẹmí, etc

name: Yẹmídalẹ́
meaning: May I remain graceful until old age.

name: Yọmbọ̀
extended meaning: A short form of Adéyọmbọ̀ or Olúyọmbọ̀, Ṣóyọmbọ̀, Akínyọmbọ̀, etc.

name: adábalẹ̀
meaning: Of palm wine: One freshly fetched, that hasn't reached the ground.

name: àgbálájọbí
meaning: One jointly born by the whole world.

name: ìfẹ́olú
meaning: 1. The love of God. 2. The will of God.

name: ìjìtọ̀nà
meaning: The (child of the) wind follows the right path.

name: ochún eletí elegguá
meaning: This name is rather common among initiates of Cuban Orisa religion known as Regla de Ocha/Santería/Lucumí religion. They have given various theories as to its meaning, including “someone who has both Oshun (Ọ̀ṣun) and Elegguá (Ẹlẹ́gbáa) deities.” This name is derived from Ọ̀ṣúntiléwá or Ọ̀ṣúnlátiléwá - Ọ̀ṣun has come from home
gloss: [{'Ọ̀ṣun': ' - one of the Yorùbá river deities'}]

name: Òhú
meaning: A child born with a vestigial sixth finger.
extended meaning: This is an orúkọ àmútọ̀runwá (literally 'brought with him/her from heaven'), a name pre-determined due to the unique nature of their birth.

name: Ṣaléwá
meaning: (One who) picks houses to come to.

name: Ṣàdáre
meaning: Orìṣà gave blessing. Òrìṣà vindicated me.

name: Ṣàdẹ̀kọ̀
meaning: The Òrìṣà became the obstacle (to evil)

name: Ṣàdẹ̀là
meaning: 1. Òrìshà becomes Ẹ̀là (or becomes clear). 2. Òrìṣà offered clarity. [verification needed]. 3. Ọbatálá has arrived into wealth.

name: Ṣàngówùnmí
gloss: [{'ṣàngó': ' - Ṣàngo, the Yorùbá god of thunder'}]

name: Ṣàṣọrẹ́
meaning: The Òriṣà has provided a whip.
extended meaning: This is a notable chieftaincy title among the Ondo people

name: Ṣeéńi
extended meaning: This is a common short form of Ọláṣeéní.  See also Ọláṣení, Ṣení

name: Ṣelére
meaning: One who is born to set the house/family aright.

name: Ṣeun
extended meaning: This is a common short form of a longer name: Olúwaṣeun, Ṣeunfúnmi, Adéṣeun, etc.

name: Ṣewéjẹ́
meaning: (One who) prepares the leaves that heal.

name: Ṣèyíṣayọ̀
meaning: Let this be a cause for joy.

name: Ṣèyí
extended meaning: The name is a shortened form of Olúwaṣèyí, Adéṣèyí, etc.

name: Ṣhódípẹ̀
meaning: The fertitlity god repaid our debts.

name: Ṣíkúadé
meaning: Disclose the death of the king.
extended meaning: The story goes that a man who disclosed a plot that had been set to take the life of a king eventually changed his name to reflect the act, and his generation has borne the name ever since.

name: Ṣílẹ̀kùnọlà
extended meaning: Usually a shorter form of Olúwaṣílẹ̀kùnọlà (God opens the door to success).

name: Ṣodiípọ̀
meaning: The sorcerer has become a multitude.
extended meaning: The name is often spelt, incorrectly, as Ṣódipọ̀.

name: Ṣògo
extended meaning: This is a common short form of Olúwaṣògo.

name: Ṣòwòrẹ́
meaning: One who makes business with the purpose of making friends.

name: Ṣóbàjò
meaning: The sorcerer returns from a journey.

name: Ṣóbítàn
meaning: The sorcerer gave birth to stories.

name: Ṣóbíyi
meaning: The god of fertility birthed this.

name: Ṣóbóyèjo
meaning: The sorcerer (or Òrìṣà oko, the god of fertility) is at one with honour/chieftaincy.
gloss: [{'oṣó': ' - òrìsà oko (the god of fertility), sorcerer'}]

name: Ṣóbẹ̀rù
meaning: The Oṣó deserves to be feared.
gloss: [{'(o)só': ' - sorcerer, Oṣó divinity of fertility and farming, òriṣa oko'}]

name: Ṣóbọlá
extended meaning: The root Oṣó in most Yorùbá names comes from the deity of farming and fertility called Òrìṣà Oko. But the word "Oṣó" also means the same as "wizard" or "sorcerer" which is the interpretation that most people, including the name's most famous ambassador (Wọlé Ṣóyínka), uses. Read more about the root of common Yorùbá names (and their mistranslations) here: https://www.facebook.com/agadeniran/posts/10206154527806205

name: Ṣódàpọ̀
gloss: [{'oṣó': ' - the god of fertility, òrìṣà oko'}]

name: Ṣódádé
meaning: The sorcerer has a crown on.

name: Ṣódípẹ̀
meaning: The sorcerer has granted my request.

name: Ṣódùnkẹ́
meaning: The sorcerer is pleasant to cherish.

name: Ṣófowótẹ̀
meaning: One the sorcerer used money to commission. [verification needed]

name: Ṣófúnmádé
meaning: The sorcerer gave (me) with royalty. [verification needed]

name: Ṣófẹ́nwá
meaning: The sorcerer came to find me.

name: Ṣófọlábọ̀
meaning: The sorcerer has returned with wealth.
gloss: [{'oṣó': ' - sorcerer, Oṣó divinity of fertility and farming, òriṣa oko'}]

name: Ṣógbàmímú
gloss: [{'oṣó': ' - sorcerers, the elders, the god of fertility'}]

name: Ṣókúnbi
meaning: The sorcerer (is) added to the family.

name: Ṣólàtẹ̀
extended meaning: If you know the meaning of this name, please send it to us using the "improve this entry" above.

name: Ṣómólú
meaning: 1. The sorcerer became prominent. 2. The sorcerer took the prominent one.
extended meaning: Oṣó has also been said to be a short form for Òrìṣà Oko.

name: Ṣómẹ́fun
meaning: The fertility god picks up chalk/purity.

name: Ṣómọ̀rìn
extended meaning: The larger implication of this name is that the child, born to the family of sorcerers, came at the right time, hence "walks well."

name: Ṣónáìkè
meaning: The fertility god (Òrìṣà Oko) has become famous.
extended meaning:
See also: Ṣónóìkí.
----
The root Oṣó in most Yorùbá names comes from the deity of farming and fertility called Òrìṣà Oko. But the word "Oṣó" also means the same as "wizard" or "sorcerer" which is the interpretation that most people, including the name's most famous ambassador (Wọlé Ṣóyínka), uses. Read more about the root of common Yorùbá names (and their mistranslations) here: https://www.facebook.com/agadeniran/posts/10206154527806205

name: Ṣónibárẹ́
meaning: 1. I'm related to the sorcerer (or "Òrìṣà Oko". See below). 2. See "Extra information about this name" for other meaning and variants.
extended meaning: This name is often also pronounced as "Sọ́nibárẹ́", which, though similarly spelt, is marked differently and has a different meaning: "Beware of/Scrutinize whom you befriend." Both variants are appropriate and have been found used among the population.
gloss: [{'oṣó': ' - sorcerer, Oṣó divinity of fertility and farming, òriṣa oko'}]

name: Ṣóníọlá
meaning: The deity of fertility has honour.
gloss: [{'oṣó': ' - òrìṣà oko, the deity of fertility'}]

name: Ṣónóìkí
meaning: The sorcerer/fertility god (Òrìṣà Oko) is famous.

name: Ṣónẹ́kàn
meaning: The fertility god has got an offshoot.
extended meaning: Oṣó is also often interpreted as 'sorcerer'.

name: Ṣónọ́lá
extended meaning: The root Oṣó in most Yorùbá names comes from the deity of farming and fertility called Òrìṣà Oko. But the word "Oṣó" also means the same as "wizard" or "sorcerer" which is the interpretation that most people, including the name's most famous ambassador (Wọlé Ṣóyínka), uses. Read more about the root of common Yorùbá names (and their mistranslations) here: https://www.facebook.com/agadeniran/posts/10206154527806205

name: Ṣóríyàn
meaning: The child whom the sorcerer (or the Òrìsà oko) has deliberately selected.

name: Ṣórungbé
meaning: The sorcerer finds something to carry.
gloss: [{'oṣo': ' - sorcerer, Oṣó divinity of fertility and farming, òriṣa oko'}]

name: Ṣótiléwá
meaning: The fertility god came from inside the house.

name: Ṣótilóyè
meaning: The wise one has been honoured.
gloss: [{'oṣó': ' - the sorcerer, the wise one, the elder, òrìṣà oko'}]

name: Ṣótìmẹ́yìn
meaning: The sorcerer backs me. The sorcerer supports me.

name: Ṣótọ́lá
gloss: [{'oṣó': ' - sorcerer, Oṣó divinity of fertility and farming, òriṣa oko'}]

name: Ṣówùmí
gloss: [{'oṣó': ' - sorcerer, Oṣó divinity of fertility and farming, òriṣa oko'}]

name: Ṣówùnmí
meaning: The Òrìṣà Oko is attractive/desirable to me (as my deity).
gloss: [{'oṣó': ' - sorcerer, Oṣó divinity of fertility and farming, òriṣa oko'}]

name: Ṣówẹ̀mímọ́
meaning: The Oṣó divinity washed me clean.

name: Ṣóṣínà
gloss: [{'oṣó': ' - sorcerer, Oṣó divinity of fertility and farming, òriṣa oko'}]

name: Ṣógbàmọ́wọ́
meaning: The wizard has added to his hand.

name: Ṣólàńkẹ́
meaning: The sorcerer is whom we're caring for.
extended meaning: Apart from being the word for "sorcerer", Oṣó is also the name for the Yorùbá deity of farming and fertility, Òrìṣa oko.
gloss: [{'oṣó': ' - sorcerer, Oṣó divinity of fertility and farming, òriṣa oko'}]

name: Ṣówándé
meaning: The wizard has sought me here.

name: Ṣóyínká
extended meaning:
The root Oṣó in most Yorùbá names comes from the deity of farming and fertility called Òrìṣà Oko. But the word "Oṣó" also means the same as "wizard" or "sorcerer" which is the interpretation that most people, including the name's most famous ambassador (Wọlé Ṣóyínka), uses. A link between Òrìṣàokó and sorcerers may be because the orisha is a powerful sorcerer who fights against evil sorcerey. 

Read more about the root of common Yorùbá names (and their mistranslations) here: https://www.facebook.com/agadeniran/posts/10206154527806205
gloss: [{'oṣó': ' - sorcerer, Oṣó divinity of fertility and farming, òriṣa oko'}]

name: Ṣóyọmbọ̀
meaning: 1. The sorcerer saved and brought me (back). 2. The god Okó saved and brought me (back). [Verification needed].
extended meaning: Ṣó (short for Oṣó) usually refers to sorcerer but depending on the family it may also be short for Òrìṣàokó, also known as Okó, who is the god of farming and agriculture.

name: Ṣùbòmí
extended meaning: This is a shortened form of Ọláṣùbòmi, Adéṣùbòmí, etc.

name: Ṣàngóbáyọ̀
meaning: 1. The òrìṣà Sàngó meets joy. 2. Ṣàngó gave birth to joy.

name: Ṣẹ̀gilọlá
meaning: 1. Ṣẹ̀gi is wealth. 2. One beautiful like blue Yorùbá beads.

name: Ṣẹ̀nbánjọ
meaning: Ùsẹ̀n is in cooperation/agreement with me.
extended meaning: Ùsẹn is the family totem in honour of an Ijẹ̀bú-Igbó heir apparent, who was sacrificed to avert conquest of the town by enemies. Source: Odùbáyọ̀ Odùṣínà.

name: Ṣẹ̀nnáìkè
extended meaning:
Ùsẹn is the family totem in honour of an Ijẹ̀bú-Igbó heir apparent, who was sacrificed to avert conquest of the town by enemies. Source: Odùbáyọ̀ Odùṣínà.
__
See also: Ogúnnáìkè, Ṣèńjọbí

name: Ṣẹ̀san
extended meaning: This is a common short form. The name is usually preceded by Olú or Adé or Oyè, etc.

name: Ṣẹ́gun
extended meaning: The common full form of this name is Olúṣẹ́gun. The name is often, also, written as Shẹ́gun.

name: Ṣẹ́tẹ̀
extended meaning: Shortened form of Adéṣẹ́tẹ̀, Akínṣẹ́tẹ̀, Olúṣẹ́tẹ̀, etc.

name: Ṣọlá
extended meaning:
Shortened form of:
Olúwáṣọlá
Adéṣọlá
Olúṣọlá
Ọbáṣọlá
Oyèṣọlá
Ifáṣọlá, etc

name: Ṣọlápé
extended meaning: The fuller form is Olúṣọlápé or Olúwaṣọlámipé.

name: Ṣọ́balójú
meaning: One who watches the king's face.

name: Ṣọ́lédolú
meaning: One who watches the house in wait for the prominent one.

name: Ẹbíṣùrùkẹ́
meaning: One that the whole clan has come together to care for.

name: Ẹdun
extended meaning: An Aborea. There is no indication if it's a particular type of monkey or ape (Ẹdun a gbórí igi réfe réfe ) see Orlando Owoh Album "Sisi Salewa" for full story.

name: Ẹdúnjọbí
meaning: The Ẹdun family gave birth (to this) together.
extended meaning: This is a name typically given to twins, and it takes root from the word "Ẹdun" which is the Colobus monkey known for giving birth to two children at once.

name: Ẹfunlabí
meaning: We have given birth to purity.
extended meaning: This is a name peculiar to worshipers of Ọ̀ṣun and Ọbàtálá.

name: Ẹfunmirè
extended meaning: Chosen from Odù Òfún Ogbè. This is a name given to a child in the Ọbàtálá worship. Ẹfun means chalk, and it is the sign of purity for initiates.
gloss: [{'ẹfun': ' - bachalk, purity (a symbol of Ọbàtálá worship)'}]

name: Ẹfúnbọ́ládé
meaning: The child of an O̩bàtálá adherent came with wealth.

name: Ẹfúníyì
extended meaning:
Ẹfun (chalk) is a symbol of the god Ọbàtálá or the goddess Ọ̀ṣun. So the name may refer to a devotee of either god.

See Ẹfúnníyì.

name: Ẹfúnlọ́lá
gloss: [{'ẹfun': ' - chalk, as representative of purity or the Ọ̀ṣun/Ọbàtálá worship'}]

name: Ẹfúnpọ̀róyè
meaning: Ọbàtálá/purity is the source of honour.
gloss: [{'Ẹfún': ' - A symbol representing the god Ọbátala and purity'}]

name: Ẹfúnrántí
extended meaning: Names bearing the Ẹfun root are usually from the devotees of Ọbàtálá, the god of creativity and fertility.
gloss: [{'ẹfun': ' - whiteness, purity, the Ẹfun divinity of fertility'}]

name: Ẹfúnsetán
extended meaning: Names with Ẹfun are given to people belonging to the devotees of Ọbàtálá, the god of creativity and fertility.

name: Ẹfúntàjò
meaning: The Ẹfun child returned from a trip.
extended meaning:
See also: Ẹfúntàjòdé.

This was the name of the central heroine in the play Àròpin n T'Ènìyàn by Hubert Ògúndé.
gloss: [{'ẹfun': ' - purity (as related to Ọ̀ṣun or Ọbàtálá)'}]

name: Ẹfúntàjòdé
meaning: The child of Ẹfun returned from a trip.
extended meaning:
Also: Ẹfúntàjò.

This was the name of the central heroine in Hubert Ògúndé's famous play "Àròpin n t'ènìyàn".

name: Ẹfúntóyè
extended meaning: See also: Ògúntóyè, Adétóyè, Ọlátóyè, etc

name: Ẹfúnyẹmí
meaning: I'm befitting of Ẹfun (the Ọbàtálá/Ọ̀ṣun sign of purity; chalk).

name: Ẹfùnṣẹ́gùn
gloss: [{'ẹfun': ' - ritual chalk of the Ọbàtálá devotees'}]

name: Ẹfúnbóyè
meaning: 1. Royalty is adorned with purity. 2. Royalty is pure. 3. Purity births royalty
extended meaning: Typically Ẹfun in Yorùbá is white chalk, and white is associated with spiritual cleanliness, sometimes Olódùmarè is represented as white, as commonly represented by ọbàtálá. Something that has no blemish. In the context of the name, ẹfun refers to the purity, the spirituality of the bearer. Some would say it is Ẹfúnb(i)oyè - Purity births royalty.

name: Ẹgbukúyọ̀mí
meaning: He/she didn't let me be shamed by death. (Kò gbé ikú yọ̀ mí)

name: Ẹgbẹ́bámiwòó
meaning: The group/community takes care of this child.
gloss: [{'ẹgbẹ́': ' - community, group, team, a particular secret society'}]

name: Ẹgbẹ́délé
meaning: Partnership extends to the home. A team makes a home.

name: Ẹgbẹ́lékè
meaning: Being part of a team/family is glorifying.

name: Ẹgbẹ́róungbé
meaning: The society/company/peers have found something to cherish.

name: Ẹgbẹ́tóókẹ́
meaning: The Ẹgbẹ́ masquerade is worthy of care.

name: Ẹgbẹ́wọlé
meaning: The cult has gone into the temple. The group has become home. Collaboration has now been adopted in the home.

name: Ẹjalónibú
meaning: The fish belongs in the deep.

name: Ẹkúndayọ̀
extended meaning: It's a name given to a child when a tragic occurrence has happened some time before the his/her birth.

name: Ẹlẹ́bùrúìkẹ́
meaning: One with a suddenness of care.
extended meaning: This is one of the cognomens used to praise God as the person capable of pleasantly surprising mankind.

name: Ẹlẹ́gbẹ́lẹ́yẹ
meaning: Having the support of another is honourable. A person gains honour when he/she is accepted as kin(or peer).

name: Ẹlẹ́wìodò
meaning: The chief guardian of the river wealth

name: Ẹmósù
meaning: One who picks up the camwood.

name: Ẹni
extended meaning: A common root of longer Yorùbá names. See Ẹniayọ̀, Ẹniafẹ́, Ẹniọláh, Ẹniìtàn, etc

name: Ẹniafẹ́lamọ̀
meaning: We only know whom we love.
extended meaning: This name derives from a common saying "Ẹni a fẹ́ la mọ, a kò m'ẹni tó fẹ́ ni." Meaning: We only know those whom we love. It's hard to know who exactly loves us back.

name: Ẹniafẹ́
meaning: 1. The one we want. The one we love. 2. The fanciful one.

name: Ẹniańkẹ́
meaning: The one we're caring for, cherishing, doting on.

name: Ẹniìbùkúnolúwa
meaning: "The blessed one of the Lord. Taken out from Psalms 115:15"
extended meaning: This, as the user who suggested it proves, is a modern Christian Yorùbá name.

name: Ẹniìtàn
meaning: 1. A historical personage, one born in ways and manners to be remembered. 2. a person with history. (Translation courtesy of Prof. Kole Ọmọ́tọ́ṣọ́)
extended meaning:
The name is given to a child believed to embody a specific history that is worthy of remembering. Perhaps a notable event occasioned his/her birth. In the case of Ọọ̀ni Ògúnwùsì, he was so-named because he was born at the exact time it was predicted that he would be born.

The name is often, incorrectly, written as Ẹnitàn.

name: Ẹniolúwatófún
meaning: One to whom the lord is sufficient.

name: Ẹníbàlómọ̀
meaning: Only the one that has been hit knows (how it hurts).

name: Ẹníkúèmẹ̀yìn
meaning: The one who is dead doesn't know tomorrow.

name: Ẹníkúòmẹ̀hìn
meaning: One who is dead doesn't know what's going on behind (them).

name: Ẹníkúòmẹ̀yìn
meaning: One who is dead doesn't know what's going on behind (them).

name: Ẹnílolóbọ̀
meaning: The one who went is the one who returned.
extended meaning: Like Babátúndé, this is a name given to a child born right after the death of its grandfather or grandmother, signifying a return.

name: Ẹnítán
extended meaning:
Not to be confused with Ẹniìtàn (a child of history/stories), Ẹnítán focuses on the impossibility of the person naming the child to find any valuable human around: a sort of defeatist commentary on life.

However, there have been instances where the name "Ẹniìtàn" is spelt as "Ẹnitàn" with just one "i". Please check the entry for Ẹniìtàn for more meanings on that.

name: Ẹníwáyé
meaning: The one that has come into the world.

name: Ẹniọlárówólò
meaning: A wealthy person sees money to spend.

name: Ẹniọmọ́sin
meaning: This name comes from a proverb that says "it's the person who is buried by their children that can be considered a parent". Ẹniọmọ́sin simply means "the one lucky to have been buried by his/her child".

name: Ẹnúdùnjuyọ̀
meaning: The mouth is sweeter than salt.
extended meaning: This name is also the title of a book by Tóyìn Fálọlá

name: Ẹríayọ̀olúwabùkúnmi
meaning: God's testimony of joy blessed me.

name: Ẹríìfẹolúwasími
meaning: Evidence of God's love towards me.

name: Ẹrùogun
meaning: 1. Spoils of war (Ẹrùogun) 2. The slave of Ògún (Ẹrúògún)
extended meaning: Depending on the tone marking, the name can mean many things.

name: Ẹwawùnmí
meaning: Beauty attracts me/I'm desirous of beauty.

name: Ẹwàolúwakìíshá
meaning: The beauty of God does not fade.

name: Ẹwàọlá
extended meaning: Given to a child that arrived when wealth is flourishing/booming in the family.

name: Ẹwàdùnní
meaning: Having beauty is a pleasure. Beauty is good to have.

name: Ẹ̀híndẹ̀rọ̀
meaning: The back (or the future) is relieved.

name: Ẹ̀míayọ̀
meaning: The spirit of joy. A life of joy.

name: Ẹ̀ríayọ̀
meaning: Witness to joy. The proof of happiness.

name: Ẹ̀ríìyanuolúwa
meaning: Testimony of God's miracles or wonders.

name: Ẹ̀rínọ̀shọ́
meaning: A burst of graceful laughter. The laughter of adornment.

name: Ẹ̀ríolúwa
meaning: 1. God's witness. 2. Evidence of God's existence/goodness.

name: Ẹ̀ríolúwatósìn
meaning: God's testimony is worthy to be praised

name: Ẹ̀ríyanuolúwa
meaning: Testimony of God's miracles or wonders.

name: Ẹ̀rùọmọ́bàmì
meaning: The fear of the child gripped me.

name: Ẹ̀san
extended meaning: Esan, (a noun) is the spiritual concept of cause and effect, karma. Its broader than "revenge". It is getting paid back as a reward and/or consequence of an individual/group action(s). "To every action, there is an equal and opposite reaction"

name: Ẹ̀taòkò
extended meaning:
Name given to the third-born of a triplet in Ketu/Ketou in Benin Republic. 
See also: Ìdòwú.

name: Ẹ̀ṣùgbàmí
meaning: Èṣù saved me. Ẹ̀ṣù received me.

name: ẹbíṣùkẹ́
meaning: One that the whole clan has come together to care for.

name: Ọba
extended meaning: As a root for most common Yorùbá names (Ọbafẹ́mi, Ọbásanjọ́), the name is said to refer more to the Ọbalúayé worship than just "King". But as modernity continues to bear on the process of naming, people have had a choice to decide to what the "Ọba" root in their name refers.

name: Ọbabíìrẹ
extended meaning: The full saying is "Ọba bí ìrẹ kò sí".

name: Ọbabíyi
meaning: The king gave birth to this.

name: Ọbafúnșó
meaning: The king gave me (this child) to look after.

name: Ọbaladé
meaning: HOMOGRAPH 1. The crowned king (Ọba Aládé) ___ 1. The king is whom we've sported on our heads. (Ọba ni adé) 2. The king is the crown. (Ọba ni a dé)

name: Ọbalàgbẹ̀
meaning: Farming is king. The farmer is king.

name: Ọbalówù
meaning: It is the wish of the lord (king).

name: Ọbalúfẹ̀
meaning: The title of a local king in Ifẹ̀.

name: Ọbaniolúwa
meaning: God is King. The king is a god.

name: Ọbanífẹ̀
extended meaning:
This is the title of a local municipal king in Ifẹ̀.

See also: Ọbalúfẹ̀

name: Ọbaníṣolá
meaning: It is the king who revels/basks in pleasure.

name: Ọbaolúwamúrewá
meaning: God the king has brought goodness.

name: Ọbádìtàn
meaning: The king has become (part of) history.

name: Ọbáfúnkẹ́
meaning: The king gave me to cherish.

name: Ọbáfọlájìmí
meaning: The king entrusted me with nobility.

name: Ọbágoríọlá
meaning: The king steps on the throne.

name: Ọbákọ̀yà
meaning: The king rejected suffering. Ọbalúayé rejected suffering.

name: Ọbámuyìdé
meaning: 1. The king brought this. 2. The king that brought value/honour.

name: Ọbámúyiwá
extended meaning: The name was made from a curtailed form of Ọbáfẹ́mi and Olúmúyiwá.

name: Ọbáshọlá
extended meaning: It's commonly said that the Ọba in this name is not "king" at all, but the Ọba in Ọbàtálá, the Yorùbá deity of purity and creation.

name: Ọbásọlá
extended meaning: It's commonly said that the Ọba in this name is not "king" at all, but the Ọba in Ọbàtálá, the Yorùbá deity of purity and creation.

name: Ọbátókí
extended meaning: From Ọ̀yọ́ North, Oke Ogun precisely.With one of my progenitors as a Gbogi  or Oni gbogi who was an Alaafin. Also heard that we moved from Oyo ile to Illaji as my village house is known as Ile-Gbogi but none in the family has ever been king of the illaji since we’re not from there. Nth generation at this point since I’ve only been home once.

name: Ọbátómiyìn
meaning: The king (God) is enough for me to worship.

name: Ọbátóyìn
meaning: The king is worthy of being praised.

name: Ọbátẹ́rù
meaning: The king is worth being feared.
extended meaning: Ṣàngó Ọba Kòso was recorded in many tales to be a dragon-like, fire-breathing king whose anger could physically consume the subject of his wrath.

name: Ọbátẹ́níọlámi
meaning: The king parades my honour/prestige (for the world to see).

name: Ọbáwòmíyè
meaning: The king raised me to survival.

name: Ọbádínà
meaning: 1. The king blocked the road (against our enemies). 2. Obaluaye blocked the road (against our enemies).
extended meaning: In some cases Ọba is short for Ọbalúayé, the god of disease and smallpox.

name: Ọbáfẹ́mi
extended meaning: The Ọba is also said to come from the reverent use of Ọba for the deity of small-pox Sọ̀npọ̀nná.

name: Ọbásanjọ́
meaning: The king ensured good returns on one's labour/investment/efforts.
extended meaning: The 'Ọba' in this name has also been said to mean 'Ọbalúayé', a nickname for Ṣọ̀pọ̀ná, the god of smallpox. Or just God in general.

name: Ọbẹ̀làwọ̀
meaning: The skin is (fresh or beautiful like) soup.

name: Ọdúnadé
meaning: Year of the crown. Year for a crown. Royal festival.

name: Ọdúnifá
meaning: The festival of Ifá. The year of Ifá. The season of Ifá.

name: Ọdúnìtàn
meaning: The year, festival, of stories, of history.

name: Ọdúnmoráyọ̀
meaning: The year I experienced joy or happiness.

name: Ọdúnolúwa
meaning: The year or festival of the lord.

name: Ọdúnowó
meaning: The year of money. The festival of money.

name: Ọdúntàn
meaning: The year of stories. The festival of stories.

name: Ọdúnọlá
meaning: HOMOGRAPH Ọdúnọlá: The year of wealth/success. Ọdúnọ́lá: The year has wealth/success.

name: Ọdúnm̀bákú
meaning: The year I would have died.
extended meaning: This name can be given to a child born after the mother has offered sacrifices to prolong its life (in accordance with the divination of an Ifá priest).

name: Ọdérìndé
meaning: The hunter has returned on foot.
extended meaning:
A NOTE ON VOWEL ELISION

The phonological characteristic of the second syllable in this name is interesting. The second syllable, on the surface, has a high tone. But on examination, we find that an elision has taken place to replace the last vowel in "ọdẹ" with the contiguous high-tonal vowel marking the perfect tense (which has now been deleted). This is why the word for hunter, which otherwise has two mid tones /ọ-dẹ/, can be realised, in the full context of the name, as a mid and a high /ọ-dẹ́.../

name: Ọdúnayọ̀
meaning: The festival of joy. The year of joy. Celebration of joy.

name: Ọdẹ́bísí
meaning: The hunter gave birth to more.

name: Ọdẹ́bọ́lá
meaning: 1. The hunter gave birth to wealth. 2. The hunter met/match wealth.

name: Ọdẹ́dòkun
meaning: The hunter became as famous as the sea.

name: Ọdẹ́gbàmí
extended meaning: This is a prominent name in the village of Wasinmi in Ògùn State.

name: Ọdẹ́kù
extended meaning: The hunting profession is sustained (by the arrival of this child).

name: Ọdẹ́kúnlé
meaning: Hunters are plenty in the family.

name: Ọdẹ́níyì

name: Ọjọrá
extended meaning:
"Alárá Orunji was the founder/rallying force for Ọjọrá town in Lagos. Three  ruling houses spinned off from Alárá's descendants: Àró, Ọ̀dọ̀fin, and Ọjọrá. They are part of the 11 Ìdẹ̀jọs in Lagos (white cap chiefs) but Ọjọrá has been upgraded by the State to a ruling house with crown for the Ọba and all, while Àró and Ọ̀dọ̀fin families remain white cap chiefs (Ìdẹ̀jọ)." - From a phone interview with Idris Yusuf Ọjọrá by Buki Adéyẹmọ Bassey.
_____________________________________________________________ _____________________________________________________________ ______________________________________________________________________________________ 

"The three branches, Ojorá, Àró and Òdòfin are existing stools in the family. The sons of Alárá Orunji are Olúmókùn, Kúéjì and Fáfolú. Fafolu the 4th Ojorá became extinct owing to the fact that he had no offspring, leaving us with both Olúmókùn and Kúéjì who were 2nd and 3rd Ojorá respectively. Their father was the 1st Ojorá and the progenitor of the Ojorás. Àró and Òdòfin stools were chieftaincies created exclusively for Olúmókùn and kúéjì descendants respectively to work with the Ojorá in the administration of the family estate and the township. Ejímósù, first son of Olúmókùn was the 1st Chief Àró while Àsábá, a grandson of Kúéjì was the 1st Chief Òdòfin. The Ojorá stool has from time immemorial been filled with descendants of Olúmókùn and Kúéjì till this day. This fact is contained in the addendum of Suit 227/1918 of the Supreme Court of Nigeria. Apart from preceding the concocted modern day oral story, it is also more reliable. Prince Mikhail Ajíbólá-Ojorá, son of Late Chief Làsísì Ajíbólá Odúnsì(Ojorá of Lagos 1955-1973)." - User feedback

name: Ọlatọ́mọkún

User comment: 
"Olajide can also be Ọlájíǹde, that is, wealth/honour has resurrected. So wealth has returned or more explicitly wealth has resurrected. Like when you say Babájídé, a name given to a male child born after the death of a family elder indicating the late elder has returned. Babájídé can be read as Bába-Jíǹde, that is Baba has resurrected."

extended meaning:
A more accurate interpretation of the name is that this child (from the Ọlá family) is worth taking accurate care of.

Notes on Tone-marking: The most accurate tonal pattern on this name is Ọláníìkẹ́, but it is commonly written as Ọláníkẹ́ because of a common elision of the second "i" in the middle of the word. But without that second "i", the tone-marking isn't accurate.

name: Ọlọ́ládé

See also: Ọlọ́nàdé.

Read more about "ọlá" here: http://blog.yorubaname.com/2016/12/12/ola-isnt-always-wealth

name: Ọlọ́pàdé
meaning: The devotees of the Ọ̀pá deity have arrived.
extended meaning:
"'Ọ̀pá' here is a symbol of a deity 'òrìsà oko', I think. In fact any Yorùbá name in which Ọpá features points at the family of the bearers as devotees of that deity." - Peter Akinlabí

The name can also be interpreted as "the policeman has arrived", since ọlọ́pàá is a recent Yorùbá word for "policeman" who, in the early days of colonialism were noted for carrying batons. The baton, as the symbol of authority, can also let the name be interpreted as "the one with the authority" has come.

name: Ọlọ́wẹ

extended meaning:
This is a cognomen.
Ọ̀wẹ̀ is a cooperative society of Yorùbá elders based on a concept of mutual help on each farms in rotation.

name: Ọmátárá

See also: Ọmọ́róníkẹ̀ẹ́

name: Ọmọluyìọlá
